js
Interface ArrayLike<T>

All Superinterfaces:
ArrayObject<T>
All Known Implementing Classes:
JsArray
public interface ArrayLike<T>
extends ArrayObject<T>

An opaque interface resembling JavaScript arrays.

This interface must be implemented in JS Simulation Libraries.

Author:
J.J.Liu (Jianjun Liu) at http://www.jscripter.org
See Also:
Vars.var(), Js.array(), Js.array(Object[]), Js.array(boolean[]), Js.array(byte[]), Js.array(char[]), Js.array(short[]), Js.array(int[]), Js.array(long[]), Js.array(float[]), Js.array(double[]), JsArray.JsArray(), JsArray.JsArray(js.core.JsObject), JsArray.JsArray(Object[]), JsArray.JsArray(boolean[]), JsArray.JsArray(byte[]), JsArray.JsArray(char[]), JsArray.JsArray(short[]), JsArray.JsArray(int[]), JsArray.JsArray(long[]), JsArray.JsArray(float[]), JsArray.JsArray(double[]), JsGlobal.Array.create(), JsGlobal.Array.create(Object), JsGlobal.Array.create(Vars), ArrayLikes
JavaScript:
Opaque types can be resolved but no class objects for them can be generated into the target codes. Re-compilers must exit with error on the operations of accessing that kind of class objects. The checkcast operation to the class literal of this interface must be ignored and instanceof to it always true.

slice

ArrayLike<T> slice(Vars<?> args)

Returns a slice, or sub-array, of the current array instance without modifying it. The returned array contains the element positioned by the first value of the argument list and all subsequent elements up to, but not including, the element positioned by the second value of the argument list. If the second value is not specified or undefined, the returned array contains all elements from the position specified by the first value to the end of the current array.

Parameters:
args - A list of the argument values. The first value specifies the array index at which the slice is to begin. If this value is negative, it specifies a position measured from the end of the current array. That is, -1 indicates the last element, -2 indicates the next from the last element, and so on. The second value specifies the array index immediately after the end of the slice. If it is undefined or not specified, the slice includes all array elements from the position specified by the first value to the end of the array. If the second value is negative, it specifies the array element measured from the end of the array.
Returns:
A new array that contains the elements of current array instance from the element positioned by the first value of args, up to, but not including, the element positioned by the second value of args.
Since:
1.0
See Also:
slice(Object), slice(Object, Object), splice(Object), splice(Vars), splice(Object, Object), splice(Object, Object, Object), splice(Object, Object, Vars)
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must convert the interface invocation of this method directly into a JavaScript invocation on its current array instance without changing the method name, but expanding variable arguments, if any, into comma-separated values.

sort

ArrayLike<T> sort()

Sorts the elements of the current array instance in place by arranging them in alphabetical order (more precisely, the order determined by the character encoding). To do this, elements are first converted to strings, if necessary, so that they can be compared. Note that the array is sorted in place, and no copy is made. And undefined elements are always sorted to the end of the array.

Returns:
A reference to the current array.
Since:
1.0
See Also:
sort(JsFunction), ArrayLikes.sort(ArrayLike)
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must convert the interface invocation of this method directly into a JavaScript invocation on its current array instance without changing the method name, but expanding variable arguments, if any, into comma-separated values.

sort

ArrayLike<T> sort(JsFunction<? extends java.lang.Number> orderfunc)

Sorts the elements of the current array instance with the custom ordering function orderfunc. Note that the array is sorted in place, and no copy is made. And undefined elements are always sorted to the end of the array because undefined values are never passed to the ordering function you supply.

Parameters:
orderfunc - A comparison function that compares two values and returns a number indicating their relative order. This function should take two arguments, a and b for instance, and should return one of the following:
  • A value less than zero, if, according to your sort criteria, a is less than b and should appear before b in the sorted array.
  • Zero, if a and b are equivalent for the purposes of this sort.
  • A value greater than zero, if a is greater than b for the purposes of the sort.
Returns:
A reference to the current array.
Since:
1.0
See Also:
sort(), ArrayLikes.sort(ArrayLike, JsFunction)
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must convert the interface invocation of this method directly into a JavaScript invocation on its current array instance without changing the method name, but expanding variable arguments, if any, into comma-separated values.

splice

ArrayLike<T> splice(Vars<?> args)

Deletes elements, numbered by the second value of args, starting with and including the element positioned by the first value of args, and replaces them with the values listed by args from the third value. Array elements that appear after the insertion or deletion are moved as necessary so that they remain contiguous with the rest of the array.

Note that, this invocation modifies the current array directly.

Parameters:
args - A list of the argument values. The first value specifies the array index at which the deletion and insertion is to begin. The second value specifies the number of elements, starting with and including the element positioned by the first value, to be deleted from the current array. If the second value is undefined, this invocation deletes all elements from the position specified by the first value to the end of the array. The rest of the list provides the values to be inserted into the current array, beginning at the position specified by the first value.
Returns:
An array containing the elements, if any, deleted from the current array.
Since:
1.0
See Also:
slice(Vars), slice(Object), slice(Object, Object), splice(Object), splice(Object, Object), splice(Object, Object, Object), splice(Object, Object, Vars)
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must convert the interface invocation of this method directly into a JavaScript invocation on its current array instance without changing the method name, but expanding variable arguments, if any, into comma-separated values.

unshift

int unshift(Vars<?> args)

Inserts a list of values at the beginning of the current array instance, shifting the existing elements to higher indexes to make room. The first value of the argument list becomes the new element 0 of the array; the second value, if any, becomes the new element 1; and so on. Note that this invocation does not create a new array; it modifies the current array directly.

Parameters:
args - A list of the argument values that are inserted at the start of the current array.
Returns:
The new length of the current array.
Since:
1.0
See Also:
unshift(Object), shift()
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must convert the interface invocation of this method directly into a JavaScript invocation on its current array instance without changing the method name, but expanding variable arguments, if any, into comma-separated values.

var

JsArray var()

Simply returns the array object of the current array instance.

This method is useful for JS Simulation to implement opaque types.

If the current instance is a Java simulated array and the method runs in JS Embed Simulation mode, the invocation creates and returns a JavaScript Array object as a runtime copy of the current array.

Returns:
The array object of the current array instance.
Since:
1.0
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must ignore the interface invocation of this method, that is, replacing it with its current instance.
